03831nam a22006615i 9781501736759DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20191990nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017367597 a10.7591/97815017367592doi  a(DE-B1597)545794  a(OCoLC)1198931133  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0510002bisacsh1 aHughes, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn a Complex Theory of a Simple God :bAn Investigation in Aquinas' Philosophical Theology /cChristopher Hughes. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in the Philosophy of Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tPart I. THE GOD OF THE PHILOSOPHERS -- tPart II. THE GOD OF FAITH -- tConclusion -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAccording to Thomas Aquinas, natural theology tells us that God is an absolutely simple being, identical with His essence, existence, and all His intrinsic properties. At the same time, revealed theology tells us that He is the triune and incarnate God of Christianity: a Trinity of persons, one of whom subsists in both a human and a divine nature. Aquinas argues that these apparently irreconcilable theses of natural and revealed theology are in fact compatible.In On a Complex Theory of a Simple God, Christopher Hughes argues that Aquinas fails in his attempt to reconcile absolute simplicity with the doctrines of the Trinity and the Incarnation. According to Hughes, an absolutely simple God is an impossibility, a being too lacking in structure to exist. Moreover, since Aquinas' teachings on the Trinity and the Incarnation presuppose his untenable account of absolute simplicity, they inherit its untenability. Hughes also offers a philosophically interesting, but weaker, account of divine simplicity, and explores its implications for the Thomistic doctrines of the Trinity and Incarnation.A dynamic blend of medieval scholar ship and original philosophical thought, Hughes's work will be invaluable to medieval philosophers, philosophers of religion, and theologians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aAnthropology. 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173675940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501736759423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501736759/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK